Name: displayMode

Type: property

Syntax: set the displayMode of <toolbar> to <mode>

Summary:
Controls whether toolbar items show their icon, label, or both.

Associations: toolbar

Introduced: 1.0.0

OS: mac, windows, linux

Platforms: desktop

Example:
set the displayMode of toolbar 1 to "iconAndLabel"

Example:
set the displayMode of toolbar "editBar" to "iconOnly"

Example:
put the displayMode of toolbar 1 into tMode

Value:
The <displayMode> of a <toolbar> is one of the following strings:

- "default" — the platform's default presentation.
- "iconOnly" — items show only their icon image.
- "labelOnly" — items show only their text label.
- "iconAndLabel" — items show both the icon and the label.

By default, the <displayMode> of a newly created <toolbar> is "default".

Description:
Use the <displayMode> property to control how toolbar items are rendered.
The visual result depends on the platform.

On macOS, this maps directly to NSToolbar's displayMode property
(NSToolbarDisplayModeDefault, NSToolbarDisplayModeIconOnly, etc.).

On Windows, icon-only mode hides item label strings; label-only mode
removes the image list association.

On Linux, this maps to gtk_toolbar_set_style with GTK_TOOLBAR_ICONS,
GTK_TOOLBAR_TEXT, or GTK_TOOLBAR_BOTH.

This property is saved with the stack and restored when the stack is
opened.

References: toolbar (object), itemIcon (property), itemLabel (property)

Tags: ui
